"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Ezekiel chapters 44–46
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-ezekiel-44-46.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/ezekiel.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/ezekiel.json (MKT text for quoting)

Key decisions in this range:
- Ch 44:2 sealed east gate → shadow: finality of Christ's priestly entry into the holy place (Heb 9:12)
- Ch 44:3 prince eats bread before YHWH → type: messianic communion meal; Last Supper / Emmaus
- Ch 44:15 sons of Zadok (righteous ones) who kept charge → type of the faithful remnant constituted in Christ
- Ch 44:23 teaching holy vs. common → type: Christ as ultimate teacher of holiness
- Ch 44:28 "I am their inheritance" → direct revelation: YHWH himself is the possession of his priests
- Ch 45:17-25 prince provides at all feasts + new Passover → type: Christ as both offerer and offering
- Ch 46:13-15 daily burnt offering (tamid) → direct type: Christ's once-for-all self-offering fulfills the tamid
- Ch 46:17 gift to sons permanent, to servants temporary → shadow: adoption vs. servitude (Gal 4)
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

EZEKIEL = {
  "44": {
    "1": '<p>The guide brings Ezekiel back to the outer east gate of the sanctuary — and it is shut. This closure is the opening image of a chapter that will define who may enter the divine presence and on what terms. A revelation of God: access to the holy is regulated by YHWH, not by human initiative. Christ is the one through whom the regulated access of the old order is both fulfilled and opened: "I am the door" (John 10:9) — he stands where the sealed gate once stood.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A direct shadow: "This gate shall remain shut; it shall not be opened, and no one shall enter by it, because the LORD, the God of Israel, has entered by it." The east gate sealed after the divine entry points forward to the finality of Christ\'s priestly entry into the heavenly sanctuary. "He entered once for all into the holy places... by means of his own blood" (Heb 9:12) — the gate is permanently secured because the entry has been made, definitively and unrepeatable. No further entry is needed; what is accomplished in Christ cannot be undone or repeated.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A type: "As for the prince, he may sit in the gate to eat bread before the LORD." The messianic prince communes with YHWH at the sealed east gate — the one figure who has a distinctive access through this otherwise closed entry. Christ, the messianic prince, eats bread before the LORD in a way no other figure in Scripture does: at the Last Supper (Luke 22:14-20), at Emmaus where he breaks bread and is recognized (Luke 24:30-31), and in the promise of eating with overcomers in the new Jerusalem (Rev 3:20). The prince at the gate eating bread is the type that the incarnate Son fulfills in person.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The glory of the LORD fills the temple. A shadow: the Shekinah glory that Ezekiel watched depart in chapters 10-11 has now returned and fills the eschatological sanctuary. In Christ, the glory returns permanently and personally: "the Word became flesh and tabernacled among us, and we have seen his glory" (John 1:14). The glory-filled temple of Ezekiel\'s vision is the Christological promise of Immanuel made architecturally explicit.</p>',
    "5": '<p>"Son of man, fix this firmly in mind, see with your eyes and hear with your ears everything I tell you concerning all the regulations about the temple of the LORD." The summons to careful, attentive reception of the priestly law. A theme: the call to spiritual perception — "he who has ears to hear, let him hear" — runs through Christ\'s teaching (Matt 11:15; 13:9). The command to perceive the ordinances of the sanctuary with eyes and ears foreshadows Christ\'s demand for disciples who truly see and truly hear what he teaches about the kingdom.</p>',
    "6": '<p>"Say to the rebellious house, to the house of Israel: Enough of all your abominations." The divine indictment before the new priestly regulations. A revelation of God: the restoration vision begins with confrontation of the past failure. Christ\'s ministry similarly begins with the exposure of religious corruption before the announcement of restoration — the woes of Matthew 23 precede the eschatological discourse of Matthew 24-25. Genuine renewal requires honest diagnosis.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The admission of uncircumcised foreigners to the sanctuary — heart and flesh uncircumcised — is named as the central profanation. The criterion is interior, not merely ethnic. A revelation of God: the covenant always demanded internal transformation, not just ethnic identity. Christ makes this explicit: "A person is not a Jew who is one outwardly, nor is circumcision merely outward and physical... circumcision is circumcision of the heart, by the Spirit" (Rom 2:28-29). The heart-circumcision that 44:7 requires is what Christ provides through the Spirit.</p>',
    "8": '<p>"You have not kept charge of my holy things; instead you have appointed others to keep charge of my sanctuary for yourselves." Delegated, casual handling of what belongs to YHWH. A revelation of God: holy things require personal, not delegated, care. Christ fulfills this perfectly — he does not delegate the work of atonement but performs it himself. "By a single offering he has perfected for all time those who are being sanctified" (Heb 10:14). The casual delegation condemned in 44:8 is overcome by Christ\'s direct, personal offering of himself.</p>',
    "9": '<p>"No foreigner, uncircumcised in heart and flesh, among all the foreigners living among the people of Israel, shall enter my sanctuary." The criterion for access is circumcision of heart, not of ethnic origin. A revelation of God that prepares for the gospel: the true criterion was never ethnic but always spiritual. In Christ, all who receive the circumcision of heart through faith (Col 2:11-12) — Jew or Gentile — have access to the divine presence. The "dividing wall" between Jew and Gentile (Eph 2:14) is not removed by lowering the standard but by Christ extending heart-transformation to all.</p>',
    "10": '<p>The Levites who went far from YHWH in Israel\'s apostasy bear the consequences of their iniquity — they will carry their shame. A revelation of God: faithfulness and unfaithfulness in the covenant are not forgotten but are part of the permanent record that shapes the restored order. There are consequences even within restoration. Christ does not erase the moral order of consequence — he absorbs it (2 Cor 5:21) so that those in him face consequences redeemed of their condemning force.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The straying Levites will serve as gatekeepers and temple servants, slaughtering burnt offerings and fellowship offerings — a ministry of service, not of direct priestly access. A revelation of God: restoration does not mean the past is irrelevant; it is incorporated with appropriate adjustment. Christ\'s body, the church, has differentiated gifts and functions (1 Cor 12:4-11) — not everyone performs the same function, but all serve in the unified ministry of the new temple.</p>',
    "12": '<p>They served the people before idols and became a stumbling block to Israel\'s iniquity — therefore YHWH swears against them. A revelation of God: leaders who facilitate others\' sin bear amplified accountability. Christ\'s warning about millstones for those who cause little ones to stumble (Matt 18:6) operates on the same principle. Leadership in the covenant community carries a weight of accountability that Christ\'s followers must take seriously.</p>',
    "13": '<p>The straying Levites shall not come near YHWH as priests, nor touch the most holy things. A revelation of God: fitness for the most intimate divine service is not automatic even for those who are restored. Christ is the one who uniquely qualifies for the most intimate priestly access — "holy, innocent, unstained, separated from sinners" (Heb 7:26). His qualifications for the high priestly role come not from Zadokite descent but from his own nature.</p>',
    "14": '<p>They are assigned charge of the temple — all its service and maintenance. Restoration to service, not to the highest honor. A revelation of God: grace restores the fallen, but the moral order of the restoration reflects the shape of the failure. In Christ, the highest honor is reserved for him alone; those who serve in the church are given roles consistent with their gifts and faithfulness (1 Cor 3:8, "each will be rewarded according to his own labor").</p>',
    "15": '<p>The sons of Zadok who kept charge of the sanctuary when Israel went astray — they shall draw near to minister. A type: <em>Zadok</em> means "righteous one." The Zadokite line, faithful in apostasy, points toward Christ as the truly Righteous One (<em>tsaddiq</em>) who is the sole basis of priestly access in the new order. Peter calls Christ "the Holy and Righteous One" (Acts 3:14). The Zadokites who kept charge are the shadow; Christ, who perfectly kept every divine charge, is the substance.</p>',
    "16": '<p>"They shall enter my sanctuary, draw near to my table to minister to me, and keep my charge." Direct access — entering the sanctuary, drawing near the table. A type: the table before YHWH (the table/altar identified in 41:22 as the <em>shulchan lifnei YHWH</em>) is the forerunner of the Lord\'s Table at which Christ presides. The Zadokite priest who draws near to serve at the divine table is the type of Christ who serves as both host and host-element at the Supper.</p>',
    "17": '<p>Linen garments when entering the inner court — no wool when ministering in the gates of the inner court or within. Linen does not cause sweat. A shadow: the prohibition on wool (which causes sweating) in the inner court points toward Christ\'s priestly ministry as unstained by the moral effort that would generate "sweat" — his righteousness is not labored but native. In the outer court (ordinary work), wool is permitted; in the holy of holies approach, only linen. Christ alone approaches the holiest in his own native righteousness.</p>',
    "18": '<p>Linen turbans and linen undergarments — no sweat, for they are holy. The sacred garments prevent the priest from sweating while performing his holy functions. A shadow: purity of priestly service requires an unblemished offering. Christ\'s high priestly work was performed with what Hebrews calls "the blood of his own" (Heb 9:12), offered through "the eternal Spirit" (Heb 9:14) — a ministry of pure, unstained holiness that no Levitical priest could match.</p>',
    "19": '<p>When leaving the inner court, the priests change out of their serving garments to prevent the holiness from transferring to the people. The holiness barrier — sacred cannot contact common without mediation. A revelation of God: the holiness that belongs to the inner court is guarded, not promiscuous. Christ mediates precisely this boundary — he is holy in himself, makes his people holy, yet does not promiscuously transfer what is his to those unprepared. "Do not hold on to me" (John 20:17, <em>mē mou haptou</em>) — even the resurrection encounter observes the holy/common boundary until the Spirit is given at Pentecost.</p>',
    "20": '<p>Priests shall not shave their heads or let their hair grow long — trimmed. A revelation of God: the priestly appearance avoids both the extremes of pagan mourning-rites (shaved heads) and excessive Nazirite-style dedication. Christ inhabits the same middle space — he is not the ascetic of John the Baptist\'s mold (Matt 11:18-19), nor is he indistinguishable from the crowd. He is consecrated without being ostentatiously separated.</p>',
    "21": '<p>No priest shall drink wine when entering the inner court. A shadow: Christ\'s abstinence at the Last Supper — "I will not drink of this fruit of the vine from now on until that day when I drink it new with you in my Father\'s kingdom" (Matt 26:29) — is the priestly act of 44:21 extended to its eschatological dimension. He withholds the wine until the kingdom arrives, entering the ultimate holy place sober in the hour of his sacrifice.</p>',
    "22": '<p>Priests shall marry only virgins from the offspring of the house of Israel, or the widow of a priest. The priestly marriage law guards the integrity of the priestly line. A shadow: Paul\'s use of marriage imagery for Christ and the church (Eph 5:25-27) — Christ presents the church to himself "as a radiant church, without stain or wrinkle or any other blemish, but holy and blameless" — is the Christological fulfillment of the priestly purity standard of 44:22. The bride of Christ is the virgin offered to the one true priest.</p>',
    "23": '<p>"They shall teach my people the difference between the holy and the common, and show them how to distinguish between the unclean and the clean." A type: the Zadokite priests as teachers of holy/common distinction. Christ is the ultimate teacher who instructs in the character of God\'s holiness and its demands on human life. His entire Sermon on the Mount is the Christological instruction in holy/common distinction: "You have heard it said... but I say to you." The priestly teaching function of 44:23 is fulfilled in Christ who teaches with authority (Matt 7:29).</p>',
    "24": '<p>"In a dispute they shall act as judges and decide according to my judgments. They shall keep my laws and my statutes at all my appointed feasts, and they shall keep my Sabbaths holy." The priest as judge according to divine law. A type: Christ as the ultimate judge who judges not by appearances but by righteousness (John 7:24; 5:22). The priestly-judicial function of 44:24 reaches its Christological fulfillment in the one to whom all judgment has been given (John 5:27; Acts 17:31).</p>',
    "25": '<p>Priests shall not defile themselves by going near a dead body — except for immediate family. The death-purity regulations protecting priestly service. A type: Christ enters the domain of death not to be defiled but to conquer it. He touches the dead (Jairus\'s daughter, Lazarus, the widow\'s son at Nain) and raises them rather than being defiled. His is a priestly contact with death that produces life rather than defilement — the power of the resurrection overturning the defilement-structure of the Levitical code.</p>',
    "26": '<p>After defilement by death, a seven-day counting period before restoration to priestly service. A type: the death-purification cycle of seven days points toward the death-resurrection pattern of Christ. He is dead and buried, and on the third day (within the seven-day window) rises to resume his priestly ministry as the risen High Priest who ever lives to make intercession (Heb 7:25).</p>',
    "27": '<p>"On the day that he enters the holy place — the inner court — to minister in the holy place, he shall offer his sin offering." The returning priest\'s first act upon restoration is a sin offering. A type: Christ\'s first act upon entering the heavenly sanctuary is to present his own blood as the definitive sin offering. "When Christ appeared as a high priest... he entered once for all into the holy places, not by means of the blood of goats and calves but by means of his own blood" (Heb 9:11-12). The sin offering at re-entry is the pattern; the blood of Christ is the substance.</p>',
    "28": '<p>A direct revelation of God: "This shall be their inheritance: I am their inheritance. And you shall give them no possession in Israel; I am their possession." YHWH himself is the priests\' inheritance — not land, not wealth, but the divine Person. This is the most intimate statement of covenant relationship in Ezekiel\'s priestly code. Christ makes this explicit for his disciples: "I am the way, the truth, and the life" (John 14:6) — not a road to a destination but himself as the destination. Paul\'s "to live is Christ" (Phil 1:21) is the NT personal appropriation of 44:28.</p>',
    "29": '<p>The priests eat the grain offering, sin offering, and guilt offering — and every devoted thing in Israel belongs to them. The priestly portion from the offerings. A shadow: those who serve the altar participate in the altar (1 Cor 9:13). Christ feeds those who serve him from the abundance of his own self-offering. The priestly portion is the type of the spiritual nourishment that comes from participation in Christ\'s body and blood (John 6:53-58).</p>',
    "30": '<p>The first of all firstfruits and all offerings belong to the priests — "so that a blessing may rest on your house." The firstfruits principle: what is first belongs to YHWH and through him to his priests. A type: Christ is "the firstfruits of those who have fallen asleep" (1 Cor 15:20) — his resurrection is the offering of the first to the Father that guarantees the harvest. The firstfruits laws of 44:30 find their Christological fulfillment in the resurrection as the consecration of the entire resurrection harvest.</p>',
    "31": '<p>Priests shall not eat any bird or animal that has died of itself or been torn by wild animals. The final regulation of dietary purity for priestly service. A revelation of God: the priest\'s body, instrument of holy ministry, is subject to purification through what enters it. Christ makes all foods clean (Mark 7:19) not by eliminating the principle of holiness but by re-centering it: "What comes out of a person is what defiles him" (Mark 7:20). The inside-out transformation that Christ enacts renders the food laws of 44:31 superseded in letter but fulfilled in spirit.</p>'
  },
  "45": {
    "1": '<p>The allocation of a holy district to YHWH when the land is divided — the sacred portion comes first in the ordering of the new land. A shadow: in the new creation, the holiness of God is the organizing center around which everything else is arranged. The new Jerusalem of Revelation 21 is organized around the throne of God and the Lamb — holiness at the center, all else radiating outward. Christ is the holy district around whom the new order of creation is structured.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A square sanctuary with open land around it — set apart by the perimeter. A shadow: the holiness of the sanctuary requires a buffer, a space between the holy and the common. In Christ, the barrier is not spatial but sacrificial — he is himself the buffer, the mediator who stands between YHWH\'s holiness and human uncleanness, absorbing the danger and enabling the approach.</p>',
    "3": '<p>The priests who draw near to minister receive the holy portion with the sanctuary in it. The geographic proximity of the priests to the sanctuary reflects their spiritual proximity to YHWH. A shadow: Christ is the high priest who "draws near to God" most intimately — "through him we both have access in one Spirit to the Father" (Eph 2:18). The priestly proximity of 45:3 becomes the universal access of the new covenant community in Christ.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The holy portion for the priests who minister in the sanctuary — they will have their houses there and a holy place for the sanctuary. Priests live adjacent to the sanctuary they serve. A shadow: the dwelling of the priests near the holy place anticipates the dwelling of Christ\'s people in the presence of God — "they will see his face" (Rev 22:4). The new Jerusalem has no separate sanctuary because "its temple is the Lord God the Almighty and the Lamb" (Rev 21:22).</p>',
    "5": '<p>The Levites who serve in the temple receive a portion — twenty-five thousand cubits long and ten thousand wide, with dwelling places for them. A shadow: all who serve YHWH receive their dwelling from YHWH. Christ\'s promise — "In my Father\'s house are many rooms... I go to prepare a place for you" (John 14:2) — is the personal fulfillment of the Levitical dwelling allocation. The servant receives a place prepared by the Lord himself.</p>',
    "6": '<p>The city portion alongside the holy district — belonging to the whole house of Israel. The city of YHWH\'s people adjacent to the sacred precinct. A shadow: the new Jerusalem of Revelation 21 where the city and the dwelling of God are coextensive — "Behold, the dwelling place of God is with man" (Rev 21:3). The spatial relationship between the holy district and the city is resolved in the new creation where the whole city is holy.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The prince receives land on both sides of the holy district — east and west. The messianic prince\'s inheritance flanks the sacred center. A type: Christ inherits on both sides of the holy — the peoples to the east (the Gentiles) and the peoples to the west (the nations of the Mediterranean world). "I will give you the nations as your inheritance and the ends of the earth as your possession" (Ps 2:8). The prince\'s land on both sides of the sanctuary is the spatial image of the Messiah\'s universal inheritance.</p>',
    "8": '<p>"This shall be his possession in Israel. And my princes shall no more oppress my people, but they shall give the rest of the land to the house of Israel according to their tribes." The messianic prince does not oppress but distributes justly. A type: Christ exercises authority as servant, not oppressor — "I am among you as the one who serves" (Luke 22:27). The prince of 45:8 who gives rather than takes is the type of Christ who gives his life as a ransom for many (Matt 20:28).</p>',
    "9": '<p>"Enough, O princes of Israel! Put away violence and oppression, and execute justice and righteousness." The divine demand for just leadership. A revelation of God: YHWH confronts exploitative power directly and demands justice. Christ is the fulfillment of this demand — "I have come that they may have life and have it abundantly" (John 10:10) is the anti-oppression mission of 45:9 enacted in person. The prince who puts away violence is the one who is himself put to violence in order to end the cycle.</p>',
    "10": '<p>Honest scales, an honest ephah, an honest bath — the basic requirements of commercial integrity. A revelation of God: YHWH\'s concern extends to the weights and measures of daily commerce. The holiness that the temple represents must pervade the marketplace. Christ\'s cleansing of the temple (John 2:13-17) addresses exactly this intersection of commerce and holiness — he drives out those who have turned the house of prayer into a market. Honest weights in 45:10 anticipate the honest dealings Christ demands of the kingdom community.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The ephah and bath as standard measures — fixed proportions of the homer. The standardization of measurement units. A revelation of God: consistency and fairness are expressions of divine character. YHWH does not shift standards — his measures are reliable. Christ as the "faithful and true witness" (Rev 3:14) embodies this divine consistency: "Jesus Christ is the same yesterday and today and forever" (Heb 13:8). The standard that cannot be manipulated is the character of God expressed in Christ.</p>',
    "12": '<p>The shekel defined as twenty gerahs — a fixed monetary unit. Covenant economics requires reliable currency. A revelation of God: economic reliability is a covenant concern. The gospel economy operates on a different currency — grace, not earned merit — but with the same reliability. Christ\'s promises are the currency of the kingdom: "truly I say to you" functions as the divine guarantee that no shekel-standard can match.</p>',
    "13": '<p>The grain offering: one-sixth of an ephah from each homer of wheat. The regular, proportional contribution that sustains the temple worship. A shadow: the regular, proportional giving that sustains the community of worship is the outer form of what Christ embodies inwardly — his entire life is a grain offering, the daily bread broken and given. "I am the bread of life" (John 6:35) is the grain offering of 45:13 made personal and inexhaustible.</p>',
    "14": '<p>The oil contribution: one-tenth of a bath from each cor. Oil as the regular temple provision. A shadow: the oil of anointing in OT religion (for priests and kings) is the shadow of the Spirit\'s anointing. "The Spirit of the Lord is upon me, because he has anointed me" (Luke 4:18) is the Christological realization of the oil-provision: the regular oil-offering becomes the permanent anointing of the Anointed One (<em>Mashiach</em>).</p>',
    "15": '<p>One sheep from every flock of two hundred — for grain offerings, burnt offerings, and fellowship offerings, for atonement. The sheep as the regular atonement provision. A type: the sheep from the flock is the most immediate type of Christ in the Levitical system. "Behold the Lamb of God, who takes away the sin of the world" (John 1:29) — the lamb from the flock of 45:15 becomes, in Christ, the Lamb from God himself, provided by YHWH where Abraham\'s ram provided for Isaac (Gen 22:8).</p>',
    "16": '<p>All the people are obligated to make this offering to the prince. The community\'s support of the prince\'s worship obligations. A type: Christ as the messianic prince makes the offerings on behalf of the community and the community supplies the materials. This is the inverse of how Christ\'s atonement works — he provides the offering himself while the community\'s "support" is simply to receive it. The obligation of 45:16 becomes the invitation of the gospel: "come to me" (Matt 11:28).</p>',
    "17": '<p>"It shall be the prince\'s duty to provide the burnt offerings, grain offerings, and drink offerings at the feasts, the new moons, the Sabbaths, and all the appointed feasts of the house of Israel." The messianic prince bears the full liturgical provision for the community. A direct type: Christ as the one who "provides" in the most ultimate sense — he is both the priest who offers and the offering itself. "He offered up himself" (Heb 7:27); "For our sake he made him to be sin" (2 Cor 5:21). The prince who provides all the regular offerings at all the feast occasions is the type of the one who provides the once-for-all offering that fulfills every feast.</p>',
    "18": '<p>The new year begins with a sin offering for the sanctuary — a bull without blemish to cleanse the temple. A type: the annual sanctuary purification reflects the need for ongoing access-renewal. Christ\'s once-for-all offering supersedes this annual cycle: "He entered once for all into the holy places... securing an eternal redemption" (Heb 9:12). The annual bull that purifies the sanctuary becomes the single offering that purifies the conscience once for all.</p>',
    "19": '<p>The priest puts blood from the sin offering on the doorpost of the temple and the corners of the altar ledge. Blood on the doorpost recalls the Passover (Exod 12:7) — the protective application of sacrificial blood. A type: the blood-doorpost is the Passover type; Christ is the ultimate Passover sacrifice whose blood "speaks a better word" (Heb 12:24) than even the annual sanctuary-renewal of 45:19.</p>',
    "20": '<p>"You shall do the same on the seventh day of the month for anyone who has sinned unintentionally or through ignorance." The atonement cycle covers both deliberate and inadvertent sin through the regular purification rituals. A revelation of God: YHWH\'s provision for atonement addresses the full spectrum of human failure, not just spectacular transgressions. Christ\'s atonement similarly covers the full range — "he is the propitiation for our sins, and not for ours only but also for the sins of the whole world" (1 John 2:2).</p>',
    "21": '<p>"In the first month, on the fourteenth day of the month, you shall keep the Passover, a feast of seven days; unleavened bread shall be eaten." The Passover in the restored order — the feast of redemption. A direct type: Christ is "our Passover lamb" who "has been sacrificed" (1 Cor 5:7). The Passover that Ezekiel\'s vision inscribes into the new order is the feast that Christ fulfills at the Last Supper (Luke 22:15: "I have eagerly desired to eat this Passover with you before I suffer") and that the Lord\'s Table perpetuates as memorial feast until his return.</p>',
    "22": '<p>On Passover day the prince provides a bull as a sin offering for himself and all the people. The messianic prince participates in the atonement ritual on behalf of himself and the community. A type with a Christological distinction: unlike the Zadokite priest of 44:27, Christ does not need a sin offering for himself — "he who knew no sin" (2 Cor 5:21). The prince of 45:22 who offers for himself AND the people becomes, in Christ, the one who offers for the people alone, having no personal sin to atone for.</p>',
    "23": '<p>Seven bulls and seven rams without blemish as burnt offerings for each of the seven feast days. The completeness of the seven-day offering cycle. A shadow: the perfection of sevenfold offering points to the one perfect, complete offering of Christ. Hebrews contrasts the repetitive daily offerings of the Levitical priests with Christ\'s single offering that accomplished what no repetition could: "once for all" (Heb 10:10). The sevenfold perfection of 45:23 is fulfilled in the one offering that is intrinsically complete.</p>',
    "24": '<p>Grain offerings of one ephah per bull and per ram, with a hin of oil per ephah. The regular proportional provision accompanying the burnt offerings. A shadow: the grain and oil that accompany every major sacrifice are the ordinary gifts of creation that YHWH transforms into worship. Christ transforms the ordinary elements of bread and wine into the vehicle of the new covenant memorial — the grain-and-oil of 45:24 become the bread-and-cup of the Lord\'s Table.</p>',
    "25": '<p>The seventh-month feast (Tabernacles/Sukkot) mirrors the same offering pattern as Passover. The two great feasts of Israel\'s calendar — Passover and Tabernacles — bookend the agricultural and redemptive year. A shadow: Christ fulfills both feasts — Passover in his death (John 18:28; 1 Cor 5:7) and Tabernacles in his promised eschatological dwelling with his people (Rev 21:3; John 7:37-38, where he teaches at Tabernacles and offers living water). The two-feast structure of 45:21-25 maps onto the two advents of Christ.</p>'
  },
  "46": {
    "1": '<p>The east gate of the inner court remains shut on working days but opens on Sabbaths and new moons. The rhythmic opening and closing of the gate structures time into ordinary and sacred. A shadow: Christ as the sabbath-rest of God (Heb 4:3-10) opens the gate of access to the divine presence on the day of rest that he embodies. The resurrection on the first day of the week transforms the Sabbath-gate theology of 46:1 — the gate of access to YHWH is permanently open in Christ, with the Lord\'s Day as the enacted celebration of that access.</p>',
    "2": '<p>The prince enters through the vestibule, stands at the gate post, and watches the priests offer his offerings — then worships at the threshold. The prince is present at worship but in a defined position, not inside the sanctuary proper. A type: Christ is simultaneously the messianic worshipper who presents offerings (at the Last Supper) and the high priest who performs the offering (on the cross). In the restored order, these two roles converge in one person — prince and priest in the Melchizedekian pattern (Heb 7:1-17).</p>',
    "3": '<p>The people worship before the LORD at the entrance of that gate on Sabbaths and new moons. The worshipping community gathers at the gate, not inside — still outside the inner court. A shadow: the gathered community at the threshold of the holy presence, worshipping in the outer court of the sanctuary, is the type of the gathered church. In Christ, the community\'s access is extended: "we have confidence to enter the holy places by the blood of Jesus" (Heb 10:19) — the threshold worship of 46:3 becomes the inner-court access of the new covenant.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The Sabbath burnt offering: six lambs and a ram without blemish. The Sabbath offering is substantial — six-plus-one, the structure of creation weeks. A shadow: the Sabbath offering of six lambs (representing the six days of work) plus a ram (the crowning rest) is the liturgical structure of creation. Christ fulfills the Sabbath by completing the work of new creation: "It is finished" (John 19:30) echoes "God rested on the seventh day" (Gen 2:2). The six lambs of labor and the one of completion are the type.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The grain offering with the ram is one ephah; with the lambs, as much as he is able — a liberal measure. The flexibility in the lamb-accompanying offering — "as much as he is able" — introduces grace into the regulated system. A revelation of God: even within the legal structure of the offerings, YHWH provides for proportional giving based on capacity. Christ extends this to the principle of grace — the widow\'s two coins are more than the wealthy man\'s abundance (Mark 12:43). Giving measured by capacity, not uniformity.</p>',
    "6": '<p>On the new moon: a young bull, six lambs, and a ram — the full new moon offering. The new moon marks the beginning of each month — time consecrated at its restart. A shadow: Christ consecrates time at its beginning as the one through whom "all things were created" (Col 1:16) and in whom the new creation has begun (2 Cor 5:17). The monthly renewal offering of 46:6 is the liturgical shadow of the new creation\'s permanent consecration in Christ.</p>',
    "7": '<p>Grain offering proportions for the new moon: one ephah per bull and per ram, for lambs as much as he gives. The proportional grain offering again. A revelation of God: the regularity and proportion of the offerings reflects the ordered character of YHWH. Christ embodies divine order — "God is not a God of disorder but of peace" (1 Cor 14:33). The liturgical regularity of 46:7 is the shadow of the ordered character of the God who is the same yesterday and today and forever.</p>',
    "8": '<p>The prince enters by the vestibule of the gate and goes out the same way. Consistent entrance and exit — the prince moves predictably within the sacred geography. A type: Christ\'s movements are consistent with his identity — he comes from the Father and returns to the Father (John 13:3; 16:28). The disciplined movement of the prince within the sanctuary reflects the theological precision of Christ\'s descent and ascent.</p>',
    "9": '<p>When people come before the LORD at the appointed feasts, whoever enters by the north gate goes out by the south — no turning back through the same gate. Unidirectional movement through the sanctuary. A shadow: the eschatological movement through the presence of God is one-way — transformation is not reversed. Christ\'s own movement is paradigmatically unidirectional: "he set his face to go to Jerusalem" (Luke 9:51). The movement of the worshipper through the sacred space without retracing steps is the type of discipleship as forward movement.</p>',
    "10": '<p>"The prince shall be among them; when they go in, he shall go in, and when they go out, he shall go out." The prince moves with the people — he does not remain above or behind but participates in the community\'s movement. A direct type: "Immanuel" — God with us — is the Christological fulfillment of 46:10. Christ is among his people when they gather (Matt 18:20), and goes with them when they scatter on mission (Matt 28:20). The prince who moves with the people at their pace is the type of the God who accommodates himself to human movement.</p>',
    "11": '<p>At feasts and appointed festivals, the grain offering is one ephah per bull and one per ram, with lambs as much as one is able. The repeated "as much as one is able" provision — grace within the law. A revelation of God: YHWH calibrates his demands to human capacity. Christ does not crush the bruised reed (Matt 12:20); his yoke is easy and his burden light (Matt 11:30). The capacity-sensitive provisions of 46:11 reflect the divine pastoral concern that Christ embodies.</p>',
    "12": '<p>When the prince provides a freewill offering — burnt offering or peace offerings — the gate is opened for him on any day, not just Sabbath and new moon. The freewill offering transcends the calendar. A type: Christ\'s self-offering is the supreme freewill offering — "No one takes my life from me; I lay it down of my own accord" (John 10:18). The voluntary nature of Christ\'s death is the substance of which the prince\'s freewill offering is the shadow. And because of it, the gate is permanently open — access is not restricted to scheduled times but available whenever the freewill gift has been given.</p>',
    "13": '<p>"You shall provide a yearling lamb without blemish as a daily burnt offering (<em>olah tamid</em>) to the LORD; you shall provide it every morning." The <em>tamid</em> — the daily continuous burnt offering — is the heartbeat of the Levitical system: one lamb every morning, one every evening (Exod 29:38-42). A direct type: Christ is the fulfillment of the <em>tamid</em>. "By a single offering he has perfected for all time those who are being sanctified" (Heb 10:14). The daily repetition of the tamid is the shadow; Christ\'s single offering, permanently efficacious, is the substance. The lamb offered every morning in the restored temple is the type of "the Lamb who was slain" who stands before the throne forever (Rev 5:6).</p>',
    "14": '<p>The grain offering with the daily lamb: one-sixth of an ephah with one-third of a hin of oil — a regular perpetual offering every morning. The <em>minhah</em> accompanying the <em>tamid</em> is the regular grain gift. A shadow: the daily bread of the morning offering points toward Christ who is the "bread of life" (John 6:35) — the daily sustenance that YHWH provides for his people. The Lord\'s Prayer petition "give us this day our daily bread" is the new covenant appropriation of the morning grain-offering logic.</p>',
    "15": '<p>"Thus the lamb, the grain offering, and the oil shall be provided morning by morning as a regular burnt offering." The <em>tamid</em> system stated as a permanent ordinance. The daily, morning, unceasing character of the offering is its essential quality. A shadow: Christ is the one whose intercession "ever lives" (Heb 7:25) — not offered once and done, but permanently effective, permanently presented. The unceasing morning sacrifice is the shadow of the intercessory life of the risen Christ before the Father.</p>',
    "16": '<p>"If the prince makes a gift to any of his sons as an inheritance, it shall belong to his sons; it is their property by inheritance." The prince\'s inheritance gift to sons is permanent. A shadow: the Father\'s gift to the Son — and through the Son to those who are "sons" by adoption — is permanent. "Your Father has been pleased to give you the kingdom" (Luke 12:32). The sonship inheritance of 46:16 is the type of the adoption that makes believers co-heirs with Christ (Rom 8:17).</p>',
    "17": '<p>"But if he makes a gift from his inheritance to one of his servants, it shall belong to him only until the year of liberty; then it shall revert to the prince." The servant\'s gift is temporary — reverted at the year of jubilee. A shadow: the contrast between permanent sonship-inheritance and temporary servant-gift is the spatial image of Paul\'s Galatians 4 argument: "you are no longer a slave but a son, and if a son, then an heir through God" (Gal 4:7). The jubilee reversion of the servant\'s gift illustrates the temporal limit of what is received apart from sonship. In Christ, the adoption that makes slaves sons grants permanent, non-reversible inheritance.</p>',
    "18": '<p>"The prince shall not take any of the people\'s inheritance, dispossessing them of their property. He shall give his sons their inheritance from his own property, so that none of my people are dispersed from their property." The prince who does not dispossess. A type: Christ, the ultimate Prince, does not take what belongs to others but gives from what is his own. His atonement is the giving of his own life so that the dispossessed regain their inheritance. "He who was rich became poor for our sake, so that through his poverty you might become rich" (2 Cor 8:9).</p>',
    "19": '<p>The guide brings Ezekiel to the entrance beside the gate, to the north row of holy chambers for the priests — the place where the priests eat the most holy offerings. The tour of the priests\' kitchen area. A revelation of God: YHWH attends to the practical provisions for priestly sustenance. The holiness of the priests\' eating — consuming the sin offerings and guilt offerings in the inner court — is as sacred as the offering itself. Christ\'s instituting of the Lord\'s Supper in an upper room with practical bread and wine reflects the same divine concern for the embodied sustenance of those who serve.</p>',
    "20": '<p>"This is where the priests shall boil the guilt offering and the sin offering and bake the grain offering, so as not to bring them out to the outer court and make the holy places holy." The atonement-offerings are prepared in the inner sanctum, not carried outside. The holiness is contained — not because it is weak but to prevent casual exposure of the people to what requires priestly mediation. A shadow: Christ\'s atoning work is accomplished in the "inner sanctuary" of the divine council before being applied to those outside. The once-for-all sacrifice was made "outside the city gate" (Heb 13:12) — but the preparation, the eternal plan, was in the eternal holy counsel.</p>',
    "21": '<p>Outer court cooking areas in each of the four corners — enclosed courts. The practical logistics of temple service spread across the full compass. A revelation of God: YHWH\'s concern for ordered service extends to practical kitchen arrangements. The God who attends to the architectural details of the eschatological temple is the same God who attends to sparrows (Matt 10:29) and the number of hairs on a head (Matt 10:30). Thoroughness in detail is a divine attribute expressed in Christ\'s pastoral care for his flock.</p>',
    "22": '<p>Enclosed courts, forty by thirty cubits, same dimensions at all four corners. Uniformity and regularity in the service areas. A revelation of God: the ordered character of YHWH extends to the spaces where worship is supported. Uniformity prevents favoritism; regular dimensions prevent privilege. Christ establishes the same level-ground principle: "there is no Jew or Greek, slave or free, male or female, for you are all one in Christ Jesus" (Gal 3:28). The equal courts of 46:22 are the spatial image of equal access in Christ.</p>',
    "23": '<p>A row of masonry around each court with boiling places built at the base. The built infrastructure of regular worship. A revelation of God: sustainable worship requires infrastructure — not improvised arrangements but designed, permanent provision for the community\'s ongoing needs. Christ provides for the ongoing needs of his church through the gifts of the Spirit (1 Cor 12:4-11) and the ministry of word and sacrament — permanent structures for the sustenance of the new temple community.</p>',
    "24": '<p>"These are the kitchens where those who serve at the temple shall boil the sacrifices of the people." The final verse of the tour identifies the function of the cooking areas: where those who serve boil the people\'s sacrifices. A revelation of God: service to YHWH includes practical, unglorious work — kitchen duty for the sake of the worshipping community. Christ washes feet (John 13:5) and serves the disciples at table. The kitchen workers of 46:24 are the type of the servant leadership that Christ models and demands from his followers.</p>'
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'ezekiel')
    merge_comm(existing, EZEKIEL)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'ezekiel', existing)
    print('Ezekiel 44-46 mkt-christ written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
